INSERT INTO chunks (id, skill_id, section_title, content, chunk_index, embedding) VALUES (
  '7350f78e-cbfc-5a0d-87d2-72f2cd4f2e7a',
  '53189b9e-d3a9-553b-95cb-cdf9a9eb9d62',
  'Best Practices',
  '### 1. Use for Read-Heavy Workloads

✅ **Good use cases:**
- Analytics queries
- Dashboards and monitoring
- Reporting and business intelligence
- Search and browse features
- Data exports

❌ **Avoid for:**
- Financial transactions requiring real-time accuracy
- Inventory checks before purchases
- User authentication/authorization
- Any read followed immediately by write

### 2. Always Test Staleness Tolerance

```sql
-- Test: Can your application handle 5-second stale data?
-- Simulate by comparing current vs follower read results

-- Current data
SELECT count(*) as current_count FROM orders WHERE status = ''pending'';

-- Stale data
SELECT count(*) as stale_count FROM orders
AS OF SYSTEM TIME follower_read_timestamp()
WHERE status = ''pending'';

-- If difference is acceptable, use follower reads
```

### 3. Document Staleness Requirements

```sql
-- Add comments explaining staleness tolerance
-- Dashboard query - can tolerate 5s staleness for better performance
SELECT region, count(*) as order_count
FROM orders
AS OF SYSTEM TIME follower_read_timestamp()  -- ~4.8s stale
WHERE created_at > now() - ''24h''::INTERVAL
GROUP BY region;
```

### 4. Monitor Actual Staleness

```sql
-- Create monitoring query for staleness
SELECT
  now() - follower_read_timestamp() AS current_staleness,
  (SELECT value FROM crdb_internal.cluster_settings
   WHERE variable = ''kv.closed_timestamp.target_duration'') AS target_duration;
```

### 5. Use Bounded Staleness for SLAs

```sql
-- If application has maximum staleness SLA, enforce it
-- Example: Data must be no more than 5 seconds old
SELECT * FROM products
AS OF SYSTEM TIME with_max_staleness(''5s'')
WHERE category = ''electronics'';

-- Will wait if necessary to meet freshness requirement
```

### 6. Combine with Query Optimization

```sql
-- Follower reads work best with indexed queries
CREATE INDEX orders_region_status ON orders(region, status);

-- Optimized follower read: local + indexed
SELECT count(*) FROM orders
AS OF SYSTEM TIME follower_read_timestamp()
WHERE region = ''us-east'' AND status = ''completed'';
```

### 7. Use Consistent Timestamps for Multi-Query Operations

```sql
-- BAD: Each query gets different timestamp
SELECT * FROM users AS OF SYSTEM TIME follower_read_timestamp();
SELECT * FROM orders AS OF SYSTEM TIME follower_read_timestamp();
-- Could see inconsistent snapshot

-- GOOD: Use same timestamp
SELECT follower_read_timestamp() AS ts \\gset
SELECT * FROM users AS OF SYSTEM TIME :''ts'';
SELECT * FROM orders AS OF SYSTEM TIME :''ts'';
-- Consistent snapshot across queries
```',
